README.md
     1‚Üíderive(Error)
     4‚Üí[<img alt="github" src="https://img.shields.io/badge/github-dtolnay/thiserror-8da0cb?style=for-the-badge&labelColor=555555&logo=github" height="20">](https://github.com/dtolnay/thiserror)
     5‚Üí[<img alt="crates.io" src="https://img.shields.io/crates/v/thiserror.svg?style=for-the-badge&color=fc8d62&logo=rust" height="20">](https://crates.io/crates/thiserror)
     6‚Üí[<img alt="docs.rs" src="https://img.shields.io/badge/docs.rs-thiserror-66c2a5?style=for-the-badge&labelColor=555555&logo=docs.rs" height="20">](https://docs.rs/thiserror)
     7‚Üí[<img alt="build status" src="https://img.shields.io/github/actions/workflow/status/dtolnay/thiserror/ci.yml?branch=master&style=for-the-badge" height="20">](https://github.com/dtolnay/thiserror/actions?query=branch%3Amaster)
     8‚Üí
     9‚ÜíThis library provides a convenient derive macro for the standard library's
    10‚Üí[`std::error::Error`] trait.
    11‚Üí
    12‚Üí[`std::error::Error`]: https://doc.rust-lang.org/std/error/trait.Error.html
    13‚Üí
    14‚Üí```toml
    15‚Üí[dependencies]
    16‚Üíthiserror = "2"
    17‚Üí```
    18‚Üí
    19‚Üí<br>
    20‚Üí
    21‚Üí## Example
    23‚Üí```rust
    24‚Üíuse thiserror::Error;
    25‚Üí
    26‚Üí#[derive(Error, Debug)]
    27‚Üípub enum DataStoreError {
    28‚Üí    #[error("data store disconnected")]
    29‚Üí    Disconnect(#[from] io::Error),
    30‚Üí    #[error("the data for key `{0}` is not available")]
    31‚Üí    Redaction(String),
    32‚Üí    #[error("invalid header (expected {expected:?}, found {found:?})")]
    33‚Üí    InvalidHeader {
    34‚Üí        expected: String,
    35‚Üí        found: String,
    36‚Üí    },
    37‚Üí    #[error("unknown data store error")]
    38‚Üí    Unknown,
    39‚Üí}
    40‚Üí```
    41‚Üí
    42‚Üí<br>
    43‚Üí
    44‚Üí## Details
    46‚Üí- Thiserror deliberately does not appear in your public API. You get the same
    47‚Üí  thing as if you had written an implementation of `std::error::Error` by hand,
    48‚Üí  and switching from handwritten impls to thiserror or vice versa is not a
    49‚Üí  breaking change.
    50‚Üí
    51‚Üí- Errors may be enums, structs with named fields, tuple structs, or unit
    52‚Üí  structs.
    53‚Üí
    54‚Üí- A `Display` impl is generated for your error if you provide `#[error("...")]`
    55‚Üí  messages on the struct or each variant of your enum, as shown above in the
    56‚Üí  example.
    57‚Üí
    58‚Üí  The messages support a shorthand for interpolating fields from the error.
    59‚Üí
    60‚Üí    - `#[error("{var}")]`&ensp;‚ü∂&ensp;`write!("{}", self.var)`
    61‚Üí    - `#[error("{0}")]`&ensp;‚ü∂&ensp;`write!("{}", self.0)`
    62‚Üí    - `#[error("{var:?}")]`&ensp;‚ü∂&ensp;`write!("{:?}", self.var)`
    63‚Üí    - `#[error("{0:?}")]`&ensp;‚ü∂&ensp;`write!("{:?}", self.0)`
    64‚Üí
    65‚Üí  These shorthands can be used together with any additional format args, which
    66‚Üí  may be arbitrary expressions. For example:
    67‚Üí
    68‚Üí  ```rust
    69‚Üí  #[derive(Error, Debug)]
    70‚Üí  pub enum Error {
    71‚Üí      #[error("invalid rdo_lookahead_frames {0} (expected < {max})", max = i32::MAX)]
    72‚Üí      InvalidLookahead(u32),
    73‚Üí  }
    74‚Üí  ```
    75‚Üí
    76‚Üí  If one of the additional expression arguments needs to refer to a field of the
    77‚Üí  struct or enum, then refer to named fields as `.var` and tuple fields as `.0`.
    78‚Üí
    79‚Üí  ```rust
    80‚Üí  #[derive(Error, Debug)]
    81‚Üí  pub enum Error {
    82‚Üí      #[error("first letter must be lowercase but was {:?}", first_char(.0))]
    83‚Üí      WrongCase(String),
    84‚Üí      #[error("invalid index {idx}, expected at least {} and at most {}", .limits.lo, .limits.hi)]
    85‚Üí      OutOfBounds { idx: usize, limits: Limits },
    86‚Üí  }
    87‚Üí  ```
    88‚Üí
    89‚Üí- A `From` impl is generated for each variant that contains a `#[from]`
    90‚Üí  attribute.
    91‚Üí
    92‚Üí  The variant using `#[from]` must not contain any other fields beyond the
    93‚Üí  source error (and possibly a backtrace &mdash; see below). Usually `#[from]`
    94‚Üí  fields are unnamed, but `#[from]` is allowed on a named field too.
    95‚Üí
    96‚Üí  ```rust
    97‚Üí  #[derive(Error, Debug)]
    98‚Üí  pub enum MyError {
    99‚Üí      Io(#[from] io::Error),
   100‚Üí      Glob(#[from] globset::Error),
   101‚Üí  }
   102‚Üí  ```
   103‚Üí
   104‚Üí- The Error trait's `source()` method is implemented to return whichever field
   105‚Üí  has a `#[source]` attribute or is named `source`, if any. This is for
   106‚Üí  identifying the underlying lower level error that caused your error.
   107‚Üí
   108‚Üí  The `#[from]` attribute always implies that the same field is `#[source]`, so
   109‚Üí  you don't ever need to specify both attributes.
   110‚Üí
   111‚Üí  Any error type that implements `std::error::Error` or dereferences to `dyn
   112‚Üí  std::error::Error` will work as a source.
   113‚Üí
   114‚Üí  ```rust
   115‚Üí  #[derive(Error, Debug)]
   116‚Üí  pub struct MyError {
   117‚Üí      msg: String,
   118‚Üí      #[source]  // optional if field name is `source`
   119‚Üí      source: anyhow::Error,
   120‚Üí  }
   121‚Üí  ```
   122‚Üí
   123‚Üí- The Error trait's `provide()` method is implemented to provide whichever field
   124‚Üí  has a type named `Backtrace`, if any, as a `std::backtrace::Backtrace`. Using
   125‚Üí  `Backtrace` in errors requires a nightly compiler with Rust version 1.73 or
   126‚Üí  newer.
   127‚Üí
   128‚Üí  ```rust
   129‚Üí  use std::backtrace::Backtrace;
   130‚Üí
   131‚Üí  #[derive(Error, Debug)]
   132‚Üí  pub struct MyError {
   133‚Üí      msg: String,
   134‚Üí      backtrace: Backtrace,  // automatically detected
   135‚Üí  }
   136‚Üí  ```
   137‚Üí
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   211‚Üí## Comparison to anyhow
   213‚ÜíUse thiserror if you care about designing your own dedicated error type(s) so
   214‚Üíthat the caller receives exactly the information that you choose in the event of
   215‚Üífailure. This most often applies to library-like code. Use [Anyhow] if you don't
   216‚Üícare what error type your functions return, you just want it to be easy. This is
   217‚Üícommon in application-like code.
   218‚Üí
   219‚Üí[Anyhow]: https://github.com/dtolnay/anyhow
